162—182 No Spanish girls will sing and toss a fandango to the clapping of my guests3 though wives at their husbands’ sides sit to watch what one would blush but to name in their hearing. Such sports are sins in the poor; to the rich they are nettles of jaded appetite, condoned or admired for ‘such wild tricks as gentlemen should have.’ At my board expect other entertain- ment: Homer and his rival Virgil shall be read; what need of trained voice to give effect to verse like theirs ?
